		@H Additional Information @L 
		Rome is still in its republic stage, so treat requests from "Caesar" as if they were from the Roman Senate instead. The campaign's timeline is highly varied, so some creative liberties were taken, especially regarding the empire map. Numerous Greek trading cities were, at this time, not under Roman suzerainty. @L@L
		Keep in mind that taverns can serve as a supplement to theaters although you may need to import meat or fish to increase its service quality. Taverns can only access meat or fish from a granary, not a warehouse. Taverns will always require wine to provide entertainment which is consumed per walker spawned by the building. @L@L
		If dock sites are crowded and you wish for more industry, it's useful to bring imported raw resources such as iron elsewhere on the map for processing and sending the finished goods back to sell by using cart depots. Depots especially excel at transporting food to housing areas located further away.@L@L
		If you wish, constructing a Grand Temple to Venus with the Genetrix epithet would also grant all houses with access to Venus priests increased entertainment and desirability, bypassing the other options. @L@L
		Note that the campaign will often have a map further in history come later; the timeline was originally poorly placed, even hundreds of years before the city you play on would be founded. This is no longer the case and dates reflect this, but creative liberty needed to be taken and the obvious nonsensical Caesar and immortal governor narrative is still used in order to preserve the feel of the game. @L@L
		The general narrative with historical background will however try to follow the natural timeline of Roman innovation and happenings. @L@L
