		@H Historical Background @L
		Capua was known as the proverbial home of gladiatorial combat. Romans used the same word ludi to denote gladiatorial games, as well as the schools which saw to the practice of such games. Ludi would be owned by a lanista who would be responsible for the training of new gladiators and arranging games with the elite. At first, gladiatorial combat was exclusive to funerary feasts and private celebrations of the upper class, but later became a staple of Roman entertainment. @L@L
		Dealing with a lanista was seen as unsavory and unpleasant, since they often tried to hedge bets or bargain for better deals. They were seen by most Romans in much the same way as brothel-keepers. @L@L
		We might imagine gladiators fighting to the death, but this was a rather uncommon occurrence. If a fight was to the death, it would be advertised as such and therefore was a rare sight that drew much attention. While a lot of people certainly did meet their end in this fashion, if a gladiator was defeated but fought valiantly, they would often be spared. Lanistae would also be reluctant to lose their expensive gladiators in a fight that was not worth the investment. @L@L
		Another common misconception is that all gladiators were slaves. While prisoners of war, criminals, and slaves in general would become gladiators, it was not uncommon for ordinary citizens to enter the arena via contract, either to pay off debts or to try and become famous. Roman women were famously known to elope with gladiators even though they were often disfigured and uneducated. @L@L
		It was in Capua where the famous Spartacus was trained and started his uprising in 73 BC. @L@L

